MB(1)                            User Manuals                            MB(1)



NNAAMMEE
       mb - a simple mailbox utility


SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       mmbb ----hheellpp
       mmbb ----lliisstt
       mmbb [----mmaaiillddiirr _d_i_r]
       mmbb [----mmaaiillddiirr _d_i_r] ----uuiidd _u_i_d
       mmbb  [----mmaaiillddiirr  _d_i_r]  ----uuiidd _u_i_d [----ttooggggllee _f_l_a_g_s] [----sseett _f_l_a_g_s] [----uunnsseett
       _f_l_a_g_s]


DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       mmbb is a simple utility for basic  operations  on  mail  stored  in  the
       mmaaiillddiirr  format. It is intended to be used in scripts, but it should be
       useable by itself.

       The program has five main modes of operation, corresponding to the five
       lines in the SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS above:
         * Show help message and exit
         * List directories which may contain mail
         * Tabulate mail in the specified directory
         * Print the path of an message
         * Modify the flags of an message and print the new path


OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --hh, ----hheellpp          Show help message and exit.

       --ll, ----lliisstt          List  sub-directories  (recursive) of the MMAAIILL RROOOOTT
                           that follow the MMAAIILLDDIIRR SSTTRRUUCCTTUURREE.

       --dd _d_i_r, ----mmaaiillddiirr==_d_i_r
                           Look for mail in _d_i_r. If not specified, defaults to
                           _I_N_B_O_X. Can be either: an absolute path, a path rel-
                           ative to the current directory, or a path  relative
                           to the MMAAIILL RROOOOTT.

       --uu _u_i_d, ----uuiidd==_u_i_d   Look  for  an  message with the following _u_i_d.  See
                           also: FFIILLEENNAAMMEESS.

       --tt _f_l_a_g_s, ----ttooggggllee==_f_l_a_g_s
                           Toggle the following flags on  the  specified  mes-
                           sage.  See also: FFLLAAGGSS.

       --ff _f_l_a_g_s, ----sseett==_f_l_a_g_s
                           Set  the  following flags on the specified message.
                           See also: FFLLAAGGSS.

       --FF _f_l_a_g_s, ----uunnsseett==_f_l_a_g_s
                           Unset the following flags on the specified message.
                           See also: FFLLAAGGSS.


DDIIRREECCTTOORRYY SSTTRRUUCCTTUURREE
       mmbb assumes the following directory structure:


   MMAAIILL RROOOOTT
       Directories may be specified as relative to the MMAAIILL RROOOOTT.  To find the
       MMAAIILL RROOOOTT, mmbb tries the following:
         * _~_/_._l_o_c_a_l_/_s_h_a_r_e_/_m_a_i_l_/
         * _~_/_m_a_i_l_/
         * _~_/_M_a_i_l_/


   MMAAIILLDDIIRR SSTTRRUUCCTTUURREE
       Directories containing mail are expected to contain the following  sub-
       directories.  Each message is stored in a separate file in one of these
       sub-directories.


       tab (@); l lx.  _t_m_p_/@T{ Contains email as it is being  downloaded.  Ig-
       nored  but  still required.  T} _n_e_w_/@T{ Contains email that has not yet
       been seen. None of these should have the SS flag.  T}  _c_u_r_/@T{  Contains
       email that has been seen. All of these should have the SS flag.  T}


   FFIILLEENNAAMMEESS
       Files are expected to be named according to the following format

       _u_n_i_q_u_e_-_n_a_m_e,,UU==_u_i_d::22,,_f_l_a_g_s

       Where  _u_n_i_q_u_e_-_n_a_m_e is ignored, _u_i_d is a positive integer that is unique
       to each message in the MMAAIILLDDIIRR, and _f_l_a_g_s is a (possibly empty)  string
       where each character specifies a flag.  (see below)

       Although  the  MMAAIILLDDIIRR  spec allows for a wider variety of filenames, I
       have chosen to expect a format like that used by  mmbbssyynncc  in  order  to
       simplify refering to specific messages.


   FFLLAAGGSS
       The  table below lists the recognised flags. Any flags not on this list
       are ignored and may be deleted. As flags are  stored  as  part  of  the
       filename, changing the flags for a message also changes the filename.


       tab (@); l lx.  DD@Draft FF@Flagged RR@Replied SS@Seen TT@Trash


